{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"99238dec-c38b-41fe-b157-e4dc83a291ba","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Deep Import Chain (level1 → level2 → level3)\n\nThe project imports `level1.props`, which imports `level2.props`, which imports `level3.props`. Each import must be resolved, parsed, and evaluated during the **evaluation phase** — the phase where MSBuild reads all project files, resolves properties, and computes item lists *before* any targets execute. Deeply nested imports increase evaluation time linearly and make the dependency graph harder to cache.\n\n## 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern\n\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n\nThe `**\\*.*` glob recursively scans the entire directory tree during evaluation. It only excludes `bin` and `obj`, so it will enumerate directories like `.git`, `node_modules`, `packages`, or any other large subtrees. **Fix:** restrict the glob to specific extensions/folders or add those directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <DefaultItemExcludes>$(DefaultItemExcludes);node_modules\\**;.git\\**</DefaultItemExcludes>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n## 3. File I/O via Property Function During Evaluation\n\n```xml\n<BuildNotes Condition=\"Exists('build-notes.txt')\">$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n\nThis calls `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` as a property function, which performs **disk I/O during evaluation**. The evaluation phase is meant for static graph resolution; embedding file reads here blocks the evaluator and cannot be parallelized or cached. This work should be deferred to the **execution phase** using a target with a `ReadLinesFromFile` task or a custom task instead.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The three patterns — deep nested imports, unbounded recursive globs, and property-function file I/O — all inflate the evaluation phase, which runs synchronously before any build target executes. Keeping evaluation lightweight (shallow imports, narrow globs, no I/O) is key to fast IDE responsiveness and incremental build performance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"63904830-e872-4b2a-bd9f-a339e10b633b","outputTokens":523,"requestId":"7404:A6C81:5B09E3:68A0BA:6A05248A"},"id":"be915e6d-9e2c-4fd6-a463-c45fd23af45c","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:25:43.540Z","parentId":"b0492b9a-e37c-4e02-bdb7-7682865cab6d"}
